00:07:48.840 --> 00:07:50.830
Pria, were you looking at me?

00:07:50.830 --> 00:07:52.540
No?

00:07:52.540 --> 00:07:53.180
Shawn?

00:07:53.180 --> 00:07:54.470
What?

00:07:54.470 --> 00:07:56.430
Yeah, you can use it
for debt payments.

00:07:56.430 --> 00:07:58.540
So societies come
together and say,

00:07:58.540 --> 00:08:01.170
you can use it for all
debts, public and private.

00:08:01.170 --> 00:08:03.000
You can use it for taxes.

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:08.376
It sort of gives it an enormous
network effect and an advantage

00:08:08.376 --> 00:08:11.140
in any economy.

00:08:11.140 --> 00:08:16.830
And then what happens is,
so many of us in a society

00:08:16.830 --> 00:08:19.590
then use it as a
unit of account,

00:08:19.590 --> 00:08:23.040
and there's an enormous
amount of network effect.

00:08:23.040 --> 00:08:26.400
Just the raw
economics of money is

00:08:26.400 --> 00:08:29.610
that others will use
it, and exchange it,

00:08:29.610 --> 00:08:32.490
and thus it becomes the medium
of exchange, unit account

00:08:32.490 --> 00:08:34.289
and store of value.

00:08:34.289 --> 00:08:38.230
So it's represented
by central bank notes.

00:08:38.230 --> 00:08:41.590
And commercial bank deposits
relies on a system of ledgers,

00:08:41.590 --> 00:08:43.580
which makes it
somewhat adaptable,

00:08:43.580 --> 00:08:46.490
and why blockchain is
interesting in this space.

00:08:46.490 --> 00:08:49.220
And taxes and debts.

00:08:49.220 --> 00:08:52.190
So then, I've pieced together
a little bit of a slide

00:08:52.190 --> 00:08:54.730
to think about, where do
central banks fit into this?

00:08:54.730 --> 00:08:57.650
Ultimately, you'll see
where I'm going with this.

00:08:57.650 --> 00:09:01.660
But commercial banks and
central banks both have money.

00:09:01.660 --> 00:09:05.770
Central bank money
are reserves and cash.

00:09:05.770 --> 00:09:10.840
So it's not simply the cash in
our pocket, it's also reserves.

00:09:10.840 --> 00:09:16.200
And bank deposits actually
are a form of money.

00:09:16.200 --> 00:09:17.880
So a little diagram--

00:09:17.880 --> 00:09:20.980
if the central bank
is at the top--

00:09:20.980 --> 00:09:25.050
and these are number
banks, commercial banks--

00:09:25.050 --> 00:09:28.590
reserves are the deposits
that commercial banks

00:09:28.590 --> 00:09:31.410
have with the central bank.

00:09:31.410 --> 00:09:34.320
When central banking started
200 and 300 years ago,

00:09:34.320 --> 00:09:36.870
it was the commercial
banks wanted something

00:09:36.870 --> 00:09:37.840
from the government.

00:09:37.840 --> 00:09:41.430
They wanted some backing, they
wanted a lender of last resort,

00:09:41.430 --> 00:09:46.440
and they would have to open up
accounts at the central bank.

00:09:46.440 --> 00:09:51.870
But today, when we
have unified ledgers,

00:09:51.870 --> 00:09:55.920
then the central bank issues
reserves to the banking system,

00:09:55.920 --> 00:09:58.710
and those reserves
are a form of money.

00:10:02.070 --> 00:10:05.130
The next thing is, there's the
public down at the bottom--

00:10:05.130 --> 00:10:07.830
Bob, Alice, and Charlie.

00:10:07.830 --> 00:10:12.120
We all have money, and
it's called bank deposits.

00:10:12.120 --> 00:10:15.230
But there's one other piece of
this puzzle, if I can get it,

00:10:15.230 --> 00:10:16.590
it's cash.

00:10:16.590 --> 00:10:19.400
So three forms of money--

00:10:19.400 --> 00:10:21.930
we can all have
cash in our pocket,

00:10:21.930 --> 00:10:28.040
as I commonly pull
out, this here, right.

00:10:28.040 --> 00:10:32.090
I'm going to watch you,
