00:21:22.300 --> 00:21:24.820
They keep coming in
and out of the system.

00:21:24.820 --> 00:21:28.720
And I'm not entirely
sure, but I think $20s

00:21:28.720 --> 00:21:32.530
are maybe three,
four, five years.

00:21:32.530 --> 00:21:35.950
In essence, these are
all signed by secretaries

00:21:35.950 --> 00:21:37.600
of the treasuries,
and I apologize

00:21:37.600 --> 00:21:38.920
for those who aren't Americans.

00:21:38.920 --> 00:21:42.160
But it's hard now to
still find Rubin's--

00:21:42.160 --> 00:21:46.300
Bob Rubin, or Benson's,
which was the early '90s--

00:21:46.300 --> 00:21:50.260
signatures on the $20 bills.

00:21:50.260 --> 00:21:53.095
Now, part of that is because the
currency design keeps changing.

00:21:56.390 --> 00:21:59.360
So $100s aren't used as often.

00:21:59.360 --> 00:22:02.870
They have turned over since the
currency design has changed,

00:22:02.870 --> 00:22:05.570
because even an
illicit activity,

00:22:05.570 --> 00:22:09.470
you'd prefer a new
$100 to an old $100.

00:22:09.470 --> 00:22:12.570
Because a new $100
is more secure--

00:22:12.570 --> 00:22:15.250
it's less able to
be counterfeited.

00:22:15.250 --> 00:22:18.010
And when I served in the
US Department of Treasury,

00:22:18.010 --> 00:22:21.040
I had to spend a lot of
time, because I chaired

00:22:21.040 --> 00:22:24.130
something called the Interagency
Counterfeit Deterrent

00:22:24.130 --> 00:22:25.390
committee.

00:22:25.390 --> 00:22:28.300
And I had to meet in these
secure rooms, where they locked

00:22:28.300 --> 00:22:31.570
us in, and you learned about who
was counterfeiting the money.

00:22:31.570 --> 00:22:32.890
Brodish?

