value consumptions?

00:23:09.940 --> 00:23:13.600
GARY GENSLER: So
Brodish is asking why--

00:23:13.600 --> 00:23:18.810
why, in, essence
is this happening?

00:23:18.810 --> 00:23:21.210
Well, a central bank has
a couple of choices--

00:23:21.210 --> 00:23:26.600
they can issue paper
currency to meet demand.

00:23:26.600 --> 00:23:29.890
And the demand is
really as evidenced

00:23:29.890 --> 00:23:32.170
through this thing called DAS--

00:23:32.170 --> 00:23:35.480
does the public
ask for the cash?

00:23:35.480 --> 00:23:37.770
And that's what's
largely happening.

00:23:37.770 --> 00:23:41.520
Or can they put some quota
system, or by government Fiat--

00:23:41.520 --> 00:23:43.590
like an India, where
they said, no, you

00:23:43.590 --> 00:23:47.580
have to hand in all
the old banknotes?

00:23:47.580 --> 00:23:51.360
And there was an
active desire in India

00:23:51.360 --> 00:23:54.730
to take cash out of the system.

00:23:54.730 --> 00:23:56.880
But in the US,
we've not had that.

00:23:56.880 --> 00:24:00.930
We have not had any real
large government interest

00:24:00.930 --> 00:24:02.770
of taking it out of the system.

00:24:02.770 --> 00:24:06.600
And so what you do have, is
you have more and more demand

00:24:06.600 --> 00:24:08.670
for $100s, as a--

00:24:08.670 --> 00:24:10.980
I'll call store of
value, whether it's

00:24:10.980 --> 00:24:15.360
for illicit activity, or
for straight-up appropriate

00:24:15.360 --> 00:24:17.220
activity.

00:24:17.220 --> 00:24:21.180
And the central bank
is facilitating that.

00:24:21.180 --> 00:24:27.450
This entire 8% of our GDP,
or $1.6 trillion of notes,

00:24:27.450 --> 00:24:32.660
is interest-free borrowing
for the US government.

00:24:32.660 --> 00:24:35.260
So there's seniorage.

00:24:35.260 --> 00:24:35.760
Eric?

00:24:35.760 --> 00:24:38.385
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I just wanted to
