00:25:31.760 --> 00:25:35.530
And then you go back
to think, is it really

00:25:35.530 --> 00:25:37.480
an intrinsic sort of value?

00:25:37.480 --> 00:25:41.180
This is going back to the
social construct, right?

00:25:41.180 --> 00:25:46.070
Because their money wasn't
good for any merchant

00:25:46.070 --> 00:25:49.130
in the south-- in that specific
South American country.

00:25:49.130 --> 00:25:51.230
GARY GENSLER: Right, so it is--

00:25:51.230 --> 00:25:53.840
if your point is, it's
a social construct,

00:25:53.840 --> 00:25:56.180
I'm concurring, agreeing.

00:25:56.180 --> 00:25:58.310
In that case, maybe it
was also a little bit

00:25:58.310 --> 00:26:02.700
of time value of paper money--
he was about to get arrested.

00:26:02.700 --> 00:26:06.180
There's so might-- so
I don't know enough

00:26:06.180 --> 00:26:07.620
about that circumstance.

00:26:07.620 --> 00:26:10.180
But for sure.

00:26:10.180 --> 00:26:14.200
So let's move a little
bit on to central banking.

00:26:14.200 --> 00:26:21.460
And I choose the US, but
it's true around the globe.

00:26:21.460 --> 00:26:23.640
So there are
economic policy goals

00:26:23.640 --> 00:26:25.560
that central banks
have taken on.

00:26:25.560 --> 00:26:30.300
In the US, it was captured,
written into law in the 1970s--

00:26:30.300 --> 00:26:33.240
1977, to be precise--

00:26:33.240 --> 00:26:36.000
something called
the dual mandate.

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:39.090
Interestingly, the US dual
mandate for the central bank

00:26:39.090 --> 00:26:42.390
has three things,
written in law.

00:26:42.390 --> 00:26:44.700
This is a quote, "promote
effectively the goals

00:26:44.700 --> 00:26:48.330
of maximum employment,
comma, stable prices,

00:26:48.330 --> 00:26:51.780
and moderate long
term interest rates."

00:26:51.780 --> 00:26:53.640
That is what's
known as, in the US,

00:26:53.640 --> 00:26:55.530
is the Federal
Reserve's dual mandate.

00:26:55.530 --> 00:26:57.990
You might say it looks
like three mandates.

00:26:57.990 --> 00:26:59.773
Simon, do you have any thoughts?

00:26:59.773 --> 00:27:01.440
SIMON JOHNSON: Well,
the central bankers

00:27:01.440 --> 00:27:03.315
will tell you that stable
prices are the best

00:27:03.315 --> 00:27:04.950
way to moderate interest rates.

00:27:04.950 --> 00:27:06.140
So that's [INAUDIBLE].

00:27:06.140 --> 00:27:08.580
GARY GENSLER: And
thus, mostly, people

00:27:08.580 --> 00:27:13.410
call the dual mandate
is price stability

00:27:13.410 --> 00:27:16.420
and maximum employment.

00:27:16.420 --> 00:27:17.970
And then some
central bankers would

00:27:17.970 --> 00:27:20.760
say, the best way to
promote maximum employment

00:27:20.760 --> 00:27:24.600
is stable prices,
depending on how--

00:27:24.600 --> 00:27:27.240
You wouldn't say that if you're
going for senate confirmation

00:27:27.240 --> 00:27:30.060
to be a member of the
Federal Reserve Board,

00:27:30.060 --> 00:27:32.280
but am I not right?

00:27:32.280 --> 00:27:33.300
That some economists--

00:27:33.300 --> 00:27:35.450
AUDIENCE: If you were up
for presidency of the ECP.

00:27:35.450 --> 00:27:37.200
GARY GENSLER: If you
were up for president

00:27:37.200 --> 00:27:38.610
of the European Central Bank.

00:27:38.610 --> 00:27:40.050
AUDIENCE: You'd
have to say that.

00:27:40.050 --> 00:27:40.860
GARY GENSLER: Because?

00:27:40.860 --> 00:27:42.402
AUDIENCE: They only
have one mandate.

00:27:42.402 --> 00:27:44.430
GARY GENSLER: They
only have one mandate.

00:27:44.430 --> 00:27:46.260
So around the
globe, central banks

00:27:46.260 --> 00:27:49.370
might have different
mandates, but almost--

00:27:49.370 --> 00:27:53.210
I would say, though I haven't
studied 180 central banks,

00:27:53.210 --> 00:27:56.870
all of them would
have price stability,

00:27:56.870 --> 00:27:59.300
or to ensure that there's
not much inflation.

00:27:59.300 --> 00:28:03.600
Because they are in the business
of having the public mandate

00:28:03.600 --> 00:28:07.340
to secure the money.

00:28:07.340 --> 00:28:10.160
That's the core thing.

00:28:10.160 --> 00:28:11.570
Now, what do they do?

00:28:11.570 --> 00:28:13.590
They manage money.

00:28:13.590 --> 00:28:17.300
And I think of it
as supply and price.

00:28:17.300 --> 00:28:19.030
So these are
Gensler's way to think

00:28:19.030 --> 00:28:22.000
about what central banks do,
but it's about supply and money.

00:28:22.000 --> 00:28:24.610
Supply is physical cash.

00:28:24.610 --> 00:28:26.860
Do we keep issuing
more physical cash?

00:28:26.860 --> 00:28:30.130
This $1.6 trillion of cash?

00:28:30.130 --> 00:28:32.273
But there's broader things
called monetary base.

00:28:32.273 --> 00:28:34.690
This was not in the reading--
does anybody want to tell me

00:28:34.690 --> 00:28:38.500
things like M2 and M3, what--

00:28:38.500 --> 00:28:40.680
anybody taking a finance course?

00:28:40.680 --> 00:28:46.540
Are you studying what monetary
base is, or M1, or M2, or M3?

00:28:46.540 --> 00:28:48.070
There's no reflection
on you, it's

00:28:48.070 --> 00:28:49.540
maybe a reflection on Sloan.

00:28:49.540 --> 00:28:50.930
I'm just asking.

00:28:50.930 --> 00:28:51.730
No?

00:28:51.730 --> 00:28:54.160
So there's different
measurements of money

00:28:54.160 --> 00:28:59.820
that central bankers
will monitor and manage.

00:28:59.820 --> 00:29:04.270
M1 is usually the hardest core
money-- used to just be cash,

00:29:04.270 --> 00:29:06.280
or cash and demand deposits.

00:29:06.280 --> 00:29:10.100
In the US system, it's about
$3 and 1/2 to $4 trillion.

00:29:10.100 --> 00:29:11.920
So about half of it's the cash.

00:29:11.920 --> 00:29:15.610
And then they add-- the
Federal Reserve says,

00:29:15.610 --> 00:29:18.850
demand deposits in a
bank are just like cash.

00:29:18.850 --> 00:29:21.970
And this comes back four
and five decades ago,

00:29:21.970 --> 00:29:28.740
started to say that the
hard money, M1 is that.

00:29:28.740 --> 00:29:32.380
M2 includes the
rest of deposits.

00:29:32.380 --> 00:29:38.180
So M2, in the US, is somewhere
in the order of $14 trillion.

00:29:38.180 --> 00:29:41.710
In the US, there's
about $13 trillion--

00:29:41.710 --> 00:29:45.260
or 65% of our economy
is in deposits

00:29:45.260 --> 00:29:46.700
the banking system has.

00:29:46.700 --> 00:29:49.520
Every country that you're
from has a different number,

00:29:49.520 --> 00:29:52.130
I'm just using the
US as an example.

00:29:52.130 --> 00:29:56.690
So deposits and make up
more money than cash.

00:29:56.690 --> 00:29:59.180
Cash is about 1/2
to $2 trillion,

00:29:59.180 --> 00:30:00.920
deposits are $13 trillion.

00:30:00.920 --> 00:30:04.060
You add the together,
you roughly--

00:30:04.060 --> 00:30:06.110
I'm using this term loosely--

00:30:06.110 --> 00:30:10.280
M2, which is a wider form of
money, is about $14 trillion

00:30:10.280 --> 00:30:11.090
here in the US.

00:30:11.090 --> 00:30:16.700
There's also an M3, and there's
other measurements of money.

00:30:16.700 --> 00:30:19.580
So the Federal Reserve
tries to manage that,

00:30:19.580 --> 00:30:22.760
and they manage it not only
by how much physical cash is

00:30:22.760 --> 00:30:26.210
printed, but it's also the
leverage in the banking system.

00:30:26.210 --> 00:30:28.460
If you let a banking
system be highly leveraged,

00:30:28.460 --> 00:30:31.460
then you're, in essence,
creating more money.

00:30:31.460 --> 00:30:34.600
If a banking system
needs more capital,

00:30:34.600 --> 00:30:37.130
then it's going to
have fewer abilities

00:30:37.130 --> 00:30:38.830
to expand the economy.

00:30:38.830 --> 00:30:42.590
And those are the big tools that
a Federal Reserve, or the Bank

00:30:42.590 --> 00:30:47.510
of England, or any central
bank has to basically shape

00:30:47.510 --> 00:30:49.190
the supply of money.

00:30:49.190 --> 00:30:53.120
But there's also things they
do to shape the price of money.

00:30:53.120 --> 00:30:55.340
And that's interest rates.

00:30:55.340 --> 00:30:58.400
The price of money is like
I'm lending Rob money,

00:30:58.400 --> 00:31:00.140
he's giving it back
to me in a year--

00:31:00.140 --> 00:31:02.090
what's the price of money?

00:31:02.090 --> 00:31:03.650
And it's that.

00:31:03.650 --> 00:31:07.970
So two big tools-- supply
of money and price of money.

00:31:07.970 --> 00:31:11.840
If you ever want to be a
governor of your central bank,

00:31:11.840 --> 00:31:15.280
you're in the Fiat
money business.

00:31:15.280 --> 00:31:16.220
Rob, any thoughts?

00:31:16.220 --> 00:31:17.580
Did I--

00:31:17.580 --> 00:31:20.590
ROBLEH ALI: Yeah, I
that's about right.

00:31:20.590 --> 00:31:24.170
And obviously, that's when
modern central banking came in,

00:31:24.170 --> 00:31:27.330
mid '70s, when the Bretton
Woods came to an end.

00:31:27.330 --> 00:31:29.920
So this is [INAUDIBLE]
floating exchange rates,

00:31:29.920 --> 00:31:32.030
and all the rest of it.

00:31:32.030 --> 00:31:34.960
And there's some good books
about this-- there was a--

00:31:34.960 --> 00:31:37.550
there's a recent book
came out, a history

00:31:37.550 --> 00:31:41.450
of the eurozone, like
monetary union in Europe

00:31:41.450 --> 00:31:45.690
is about 40 years old, give or
take the different [INAUDIBLE]..

00:31:45.690 --> 00:31:48.960
[INAUDIBLE],, his name was,
a guy at the IMF, I think,

00:31:48.960 --> 00:31:51.470
worked on the Greek crisis,
and he wrote a very good book

00:31:51.470 --> 00:31:54.440
about, right, the
history of monetary union

00:31:54.440 --> 00:31:58.000
in the European Union,
and how that worked.

00:31:58.000 --> 00:31:59.240
And this goes for a long--

00:31:59.240 --> 00:32:02.820
like end of-- taking place at
the end of Bretton Woods to,

00:32:02.820 --> 00:32:04.450
I think, the Greek crisis.

00:32:04.450 --> 00:32:07.890
GARY GENSLER: One
weekend in 1971,

00:32:07.890 --> 00:32:14.460
if I've got my year correct,
early 1970s, Richard Nixon

00:32:14.460 --> 00:32:15.750
took to Camp David--

00:32:15.750 --> 00:32:20.320
which is the presidential
retreat in western Maryland.

00:32:20.320 --> 00:32:22.930
The leaders that he needed to
get together in one weekend--

00:32:22.930 --> 00:32:27.760
the head of the Federal
Reserve, the undersecretary

00:32:27.760 --> 00:32:30.160
for monetary affairs at
the Treasury Department,

00:32:30.160 --> 00:32:33.340
who happened to be Paul
Volcker at the time.

00:32:33.340 --> 00:32:39.100
But he got together four or
five people in one weekend,

00:32:39.100 --> 00:32:42.990
and took the US off the
end of the gold standard.

00:32:42.990 --> 00:32:46.060
We kind of went off the
gold standard in the 1930s,

00:32:46.060 --> 00:32:49.720
but after World War II, there
was an international consensus,

00:32:49.720 --> 00:32:51.760
Bretton Woods, and
there was still

00:32:51.760 --> 00:32:54.280
that central banks
to central banks

00:32:54.280 --> 00:32:56.870
could exchange money for gold.

00:32:56.870 --> 00:33:00.380
So we were still in
somewhat a gold standard.

00:33:00.380 --> 00:33:04.262
And Rob might have a
different point of view--

00:33:04.262 --> 00:33:05.720
a good friend of
mine, Jeff Gordon,

00:33:05.720 --> 00:33:07.430
is writing a book
about that weekend,

00:33:07.430 --> 00:33:12.530
he was dean of the
business school at Yale.

00:33:12.530 --> 00:33:16.370
But the French had asked
for some of their gold back.

00:33:16.370 --> 00:33:17.810
And they got it back.

00:33:17.810 --> 00:33:21.560
But then the British started
to make noise, Bank of England,

00:33:21.560 --> 00:33:24.530
started make noise that they
wanted some of their gold back.

00:33:24.530 --> 00:33:27.410
And Richard Nixon
had a challenge.

00:33:27.410 --> 00:33:30.420
So he decided he'd just take
us off the gold standard.

00:33:30.420 --> 00:33:31.970
There's a lot of
historians' debate

00:33:31.970 --> 00:33:34.420
whether the Bank of
England forced it or not.

00:33:34.420 --> 00:33:34.920
Simon?

00:33:34.920 --> 00:33:35.490
SIMON JOHNSON: It
wasn't their gold,

00:33:35.490 --> 00:33:37.250
it was our gold-- they
wanted to exchange

00:33:37.250 --> 00:33:38.498
their dollars for our gold.

00:33:38.498 --> 00:33:39.790
That's what Nixon didn't want--

00:33:39.790 --> 00:33:40.970
GARY GENSLER: I see, I see.

00:33:40.970 --> 00:33:45.270
So Professor Johnson is
saying, it was actually--

00:33:45.270 --> 00:33:46.610
SIMON JOHNSON: US gold.

00:33:46.610 --> 00:33:49.260
GARY GENSLER: Wait, it was
the US gold, or the UK's gold?

00:33:49.260 --> 00:33:51.310
SIMON JOHNSON: They had dollar
balances that they accumulated,

00:33:51.310 --> 00:33:52.670
which was all fair and good.

00:33:52.670 --> 00:33:54.920
And under Bretton Woods, you
could convert your dollar

00:33:54.920 --> 00:33:57.335
balances into gold, until
Richard Nixon said you

00:33:57.335 --> 00:33:57.987
couldn't.

00:33:57.987 --> 00:33:58.820
GARY GENSLER: Right.

00:33:58.820 --> 00:34:01.220
And so the question
was, whose gold was it?

00:34:01.220 --> 00:34:03.920
And under Richard Nixon's view--
and I think Simon is agreeing,

00:34:03.920 --> 00:34:05.120
it was--

00:34:05.120 --> 00:34:08.270
I didn't know, because you're
a dual citizen, aren't you?

00:34:08.270 --> 00:34:10.727
I just didn't know when you
said our gold, whose gold?

00:34:10.727 --> 00:34:12.560
SIMON JOHNSON: It was
in my American accent.

00:34:12.560 --> 00:34:15.300
GARY GENSLER: So your British
accent was throwing me off.

00:34:15.300 --> 00:34:17.400
[LAUGHTER]

00:34:17.400 --> 00:34:21.020
OK, so Richard Nixon would
agree with Professor Johnson

00:34:21.020 --> 00:34:22.900
that it was our gold.

00:34:22.900 --> 00:34:25.760
And the British to
this day would say,

00:34:25.760 --> 00:34:27.900
well, we didn't really
ask for it back,

00:34:27.900 --> 00:34:30.469
They were making some
noises about this.

00:34:34.850 --> 00:34:36.870
I don't know if that's--
that might even be.

00:34:43.650 --> 00:34:45.353
So what do they do?

00:34:45.353 --> 00:34:47.020
What does the central
banks actually do?

00:34:47.020 --> 00:34:50.560
They oversee the
fractional banking system,

00:34:50.560 --> 00:34:52.600
providing those reserves.

00:34:52.600 --> 00:34:55.510
But also regulating
the banking system.

00:34:55.510 --> 00:34:59.860
I mean, if you're sitting on
top of all of this back here,

00:34:59.860 --> 00:35:02.470
you might want to
regulate the whole system.

00:35:02.470 --> 00:35:05.260
And that's why around the globe,
by and large, central banks

00:35:05.260 --> 00:35:07.660
regulate the banking
system-- not always,

00:35:07.660 --> 00:35:09.490
and sometimes, like
in the United Kingdom,

00:35:09.490 --> 00:35:13.210
they gave it up to another
agency and then pulled it back.

00:35:13.210 --> 00:35:13.745
Hugo?

00:35:13.745 --> 00:35:15.370
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I
just have a question.

00:35:15.370 --> 00:35:19.330
So I understand how central
banks introduce new money

00:35:19.330 --> 00:35:20.570
into the system.

00:35:20.570 --> 00:35:22.450
But what would be the
mechanism of trying

00:35:22.450 --> 00:35:23.890
to decrease the supply of cash?

00:35:23.890 --> 00:35:27.550
Would it be an increase in the--

00:35:27.550 --> 00:35:30.460
or not allowing the commercial
banks to use much leverage?

00:35:30.460 --> 00:35:33.790
Or how would they bring
money back and get rid of it?

00:35:33.790 --> 00:35:37.080
GARY GENSLER: So you can apply--

00:35:37.080 --> 00:35:38.110
a very good question--

00:35:38.110 --> 00:35:41.080
Hugo is saying, how can you
change the amount of money?

00:35:41.080 --> 00:35:43.840
And I'm going to use all
digital forms of money, not just

00:35:43.840 --> 00:35:45.310
physical cash.

00:35:45.310 --> 00:35:48.130
But off digital forms, the
way you can effect it is

00:35:48.130 --> 00:35:54.530
say that any one bank needs
more capital, or more reserves--

00:35:54.530 --> 00:35:57.050
so you're lowering
the multiplier

00:35:57.050 --> 00:35:59.390
effect in fractional banking.

00:35:59.390 --> 00:36:02.950
If you need 5%
capital, that means

00:36:02.950 --> 00:36:05.620
you can have $20
of balance sheet

00:36:05.620 --> 00:36:07.530
for every dollar of capital.

00:36:07.530 --> 00:36:12.140
If all of a sudden you
say, no, you need 10%,

00:36:12.140 --> 00:36:14.910
then you would be shrinking
the banking system in half,

00:36:14.910 --> 00:36:16.250
for instance.

00:36:16.250 --> 00:36:19.860
So there is a number of tools,
but one of the direct tools

00:36:19.860 --> 00:36:22.830
is reserve requirements
and capital requirements.

00:36:22.830 --> 00:36:24.480
It's not the only tool.

00:36:24.480 --> 00:36:25.980
AUDIENCE: So it
would be a mandate

00:36:25.980 --> 00:36:27.390
to the commercial banks?

00:36:27.390 --> 00:36:28.800
You wouldn't
necessarily directly

00:36:28.800 --> 00:36:30.990
interact with the retail?

00:36:30.990 --> 00:36:34.620
GARY GENSLER: Correct, the
Federal Reserve manages

00:36:34.620 --> 00:36:36.870
monetary supply
in numerous ways,

00:36:36.870 --> 00:36:38.720
but some of the direct ways--

00:36:38.720 --> 00:36:42.600
and it's why they also regulate
the fractional banking system.

00:36:42.600 --> 00:36:45.930
They have that direct need.

00:36:45.930 --> 00:36:48.600
But they also need, very
importantly, the third bullet

00:36:48.600 --> 00:36:51.660
point, to promote a safe and
efficient payment system.

00:36:51.660 --> 00:36:56.500
In some countries, many of the
countries represented here,

00:36:56.500 --> 00:37:00.550
written right in the
legislative act that sets up

00:37:00.550 --> 00:37:03.700
a central bank, says they must
promote a safe and efficient

00:37:03.700 --> 00:37:06.030
payment system.

00:37:06.030 --> 00:37:07.760
And if it's not written
into legislation,

00:37:07.760 --> 00:37:11.530
it's at the heart of
every central bank.

00:37:11.530 --> 00:37:13.660
They are also the
lender of last resort.

00:37:13.660 --> 00:37:17.050
When banks fail, they
come in and support them.

00:37:17.050 --> 00:37:19.990
Our central bank
was set up in 1913.

00:37:19.990 --> 00:37:23.410
In 1907, we had a crisis.

00:37:23.410 --> 00:37:25.620
Banks were failing all around.

00:37:25.620 --> 00:37:27.760
Does anyone know the
history of that crisis?

00:37:27.760 --> 00:37:30.370
Who actually was the
lender of last resort

00:37:30.370 --> 00:37:32.740
in the US economy in 1907?

00:37:32.740 --> 00:37:35.130
And it was not
the US government.

00:37:35.130 --> 00:37:36.400
AUDIENCE: JP Morgan.

00:37:36.400 --> 00:37:38.415
GARY GENSLER: JP Morgan.

00:37:38.415 --> 00:37:43.928
And not JP Morgan the
bank, JP Morgan the man.

00:37:43.928 --> 00:37:45.595
I mean, he had a bank,
he had a library,

00:37:45.595 --> 00:37:49.870
he had a lot of other
things going on for sure.

00:37:49.870 --> 00:37:52.030
You could say, he was
the Bill Gates or Warren

00:37:52.030 --> 00:37:53.680
Buffett of his time.

00:37:53.680 --> 00:37:56.770
But in sense, he had more
influence than a Warren Buffett

00:37:56.770 --> 00:38:01.750
or Bill Gates in 1907.

00:38:01.750 --> 00:38:04.360
We had had a--

00:38:04.360 --> 00:38:07.120
in fact, that picture in
the upper right corner,

00:38:07.120 --> 00:38:15.421
is the First Bank of the US in
Philadelphia, set up in 1791.

00:38:15.421 --> 00:38:17.750
It was set up with
a 20-year charter.

00:38:17.750 --> 00:38:22.130
Hamilton and Jefferson
had a huge fight.

00:38:22.130 --> 00:38:23.970
The Congress passed
the law to set up

00:38:23.970 --> 00:38:26.190
the First Bank of the US.

00:38:26.190 --> 00:38:27.840
And Jefferson recommends--

00:38:27.840 --> 00:38:29.630
Jefferson with
Secretary of State--

00:38:29.630 --> 00:38:33.240
recommends to President
Washington, veto it.

00:38:33.240 --> 00:38:35.530
Hamilton's wrong.

00:38:35.530 --> 00:38:39.510
Washington gave Hamilton one
week to write him a report.

00:38:39.510 --> 00:38:41.500
It's a really
well-written report--

00:38:41.500 --> 00:38:43.160
I've not read it in
a number of years,

00:38:43.160 --> 00:38:47.690
but I went back and read
it when I was at Treasury.

00:38:47.690 --> 00:38:50.990
One week later, Washington
signed the bill.

00:38:50.990 --> 00:38:53.980
Jefferson never forgave
Hamilton for that,

00:38:53.980 --> 00:38:55.520
and many other things.

00:38:55.520 --> 00:39:00.640
But it was a compromise
that only lasted 20 years.

00:39:00.640 --> 00:39:06.580
In 1811, we no longer
had a central bank.

00:39:06.580 --> 00:39:09.640
So we had a love-hate in the
US with this central authority

00:39:09.640 --> 00:39:12.620
in central banking.

00:39:12.620 --> 00:39:15.310
AUDIENCE: There's [INAUDIBLE]
and crypto anarchists say that

00:39:15.310 --> 00:39:18.000
because Fiat currency isn't
backed by the gold standard,

00:39:18.000 --> 00:39:19.750
and because of fractional
reserve banking,

00:39:19.750 --> 00:39:22.252
that the Fiat accounts
is worthless--

00:39:22.252 --> 00:39:23.710
I guess, what would
your response--

00:39:23.710 --> 00:39:25.085
or the bankers in
the room-- what

00:39:25.085 --> 00:39:27.390
would your response to that be?

00:39:27.390 --> 00:39:28.770
ROBLEH ALI: Well, I think--

00:39:31.570 --> 00:39:33.460
I mean, money is-- it
comes back to money

00:39:33.460 --> 00:39:36.200
as a social construct
thing, right?

00:39:36.200 --> 00:39:39.598
Anything can be money if you
want it to, almost anything.

00:39:39.598 --> 00:39:41.890
So if you've got a big enough
group of people who think

00:39:41.890 --> 00:39:44.057
something's money, then it
has-- that it's valuable,

00:39:44.057 --> 00:39:44.980
then that's true--

00:39:44.980 --> 00:39:47.567
the US dollar, and a Bitcoin.

00:39:47.567 --> 00:39:49.150
But I guess the
question is how do you

00:39:49.150 --> 00:39:50.440
generate trust in the system?

00:39:50.440 --> 00:39:52.270
And I guess the US
government generates it

00:39:52.270 --> 00:39:56.017
through having a nation state,
an army, and a treasury,

00:39:56.017 --> 00:39:56.850
and everything else.

00:39:56.850 --> 00:40:00.070
Whereas Bitcoin has this
network of miners, and this code

00:40:00.070 --> 00:40:02.260
that people put their faith in.

00:40:02.260 --> 00:40:04.850
So it's just generally-- it's
the trust in a different way.

00:40:04.850 --> 00:40:07.780
But to say, money is only
worthless if everybody

00:40:07.780 --> 00:40:10.400
thinks it's worthless, or like
a significant group of people.

00:40:10.400 --> 00:40:13.550
So the Zimbabwean dollar
is worthless, right?

00:40:13.550 --> 00:40:16.340
But Fiat money as a general
concept being worthless,

00:40:16.340 --> 00:40:19.060
I mean, now you've choice.

00:40:19.060 --> 00:40:21.280
You can choose Bitcoin, or
any other crypto currency,

00:40:21.280 --> 00:40:23.197
if you want to, depending
on your preferences.

00:40:23.197 --> 00:40:25.900
But I think it's difficult
to maintain it's worthless

00:40:25.900 --> 00:40:29.005
when lots of people use it
all the time, can exchange it

00:40:29.005 --> 00:40:31.750
for goods and services.

00:40:31.750 --> 00:40:36.190
GARY GENSLER: And I think
also, Fiat currency has had

00:40:36.190 --> 00:40:39.730
a lot of challenges and crises.

00:40:39.730 --> 00:40:43.270
Usually related to either
poor fiscal policy--

00:40:43.270 --> 00:40:46.240
that the nation,
the government state

00:40:46.240 --> 00:40:49.930
is overspending
its taxing ability,

00:40:49.930 --> 00:40:53.420
because taxes are revenue,
and then the spending.

00:40:53.420 --> 00:40:58.220
Often related to
wars, but not always.

00:40:58.220 --> 00:41:02.360
Or to the monetary policy--

00:41:02.360 --> 00:41:04.730
in essence, a lot of
printing of money.

00:41:04.730 --> 00:41:07.130
In the old days, it was
physical printing of money.

00:41:07.130 --> 00:41:08.570
In the new days, it's digital.

00:41:08.570 --> 00:41:12.330
It's the overseeing
of the banking sector.

00:41:12.330 --> 00:41:15.170
And some of the
biggest banking crises

00:41:15.170 --> 00:41:17.930
have led to
significant, in essence,

00:41:17.930 --> 00:41:20.090
expansion of the monetary base.

00:41:20.090 --> 00:41:21.890
Maybe it was lending
against real estate

00:41:21.890 --> 00:41:25.248
in a housing bubble in
Ireland, or other countries,

00:41:25.248 --> 00:41:25.790
and so forth.

00:41:25.790 --> 00:41:30.890
But we're not unique in the
US to have housing bubbles.

00:41:30.890 --> 00:41:34.010
And that can undermine
the social consensus

00:41:34.010 --> 00:41:35.870
about Fiat money.

00:41:35.870 --> 00:41:41.960
Take China in the late 1940s,
where every few minutes

00:41:41.960 --> 00:41:44.780
you had to worry about, did
you have enough suitcases

00:41:44.780 --> 00:41:47.390
of physical cash to pay
for your restaurant bill,

00:41:47.390 --> 00:41:50.450
if you were at a
restaurant, and so forth.

00:41:50.450 --> 00:41:54.190
And any country that's in
the midst of hyper-inflation,

00:41:54.190 --> 00:41:58.280
you usually then-- the
social construct falls away.

00:41:58.280 --> 00:42:01.580
But it's rare that it hasn't
been replaced by another Fiat

00:42:01.580 --> 00:42:02.750
currency--

00:42:02.750 --> 00:42:07.490
maybe with a stronger military,
or a stronger central bank.

00:42:07.490 --> 00:42:09.350
But after some crisis.

00:42:09.350 --> 00:42:12.920
Occasionally, it's replaced
by another country's Fiat

00:42:12.920 --> 00:42:16.280
currency, and there's a number
of Latin American countries

00:42:16.280 --> 00:42:18.140
that have said, well
this isn't working.

00:42:18.140 --> 00:42:20.960
We're going to go
to the US dollar.

00:42:20.960 --> 00:42:22.620
And just be darn--

00:42:22.620 --> 00:42:24.970
we're not going to
trust our sovereign,

00:42:24.970 --> 00:42:26.585
we're to trust somebody else.

00:42:26.585 --> 00:42:28.940
And remember, I've
said this once,

00:42:28.940 --> 00:42:30.960
I think, in this
class, the history--

00:42:30.960 --> 00:42:34.430
and Simon, bail me
out, and Rob, bail me

00:42:34.430 --> 00:42:37.130
out-- but the history
of the Bank of England

00:42:37.130 --> 00:42:42.470
was that the King of England was
at war with the King of France,

00:42:42.470 --> 00:42:45.830
and needed to borrow some money
and couldn't borrow it readily.

00:42:45.830 --> 00:42:48.770
I think it's like 1
and 1/2 million pounds.

00:42:48.770 --> 00:42:51.050
And some noble lord
said, well, this is

00:42:51.050 --> 00:42:53.090
how we'll give you the money--

00:42:53.090 --> 00:42:55.350
if we set up a board--

00:42:55.350 --> 00:42:56.900
it was initially,
the Bank of England

00:42:56.900 --> 00:43:02.240
was in essence a contract
between the sovereign

00:43:02.240 --> 00:43:07.550
and the noble lords that
said, we have to check.

00:43:07.550 --> 00:43:10.130
And then the war went
on, I don't remember,

00:43:10.130 --> 00:43:12.590
you guys probably won
and beat the French.

00:43:12.590 --> 00:43:15.297
But it was in the
midst of a war that--

00:43:15.297 --> 00:43:16.340
SIMON JOHNSON: Always.

00:43:16.340 --> 00:43:18.840
GARY GENSLER: All right, you're
recorded, by the way, video.

00:43:18.840 --> 00:43:19.600
Rob?

00:43:19.600 --> 00:43:21.280
ROBLEH ALI: Yeah,
the Bank of England

00:43:21.280 --> 00:43:23.323
was set up to finance
a war with France.

00:43:23.323 --> 00:43:25.740
GARY GENSLER: Yeah, was to
help finance a war with France.

00:43:25.740 --> 00:43:27.240
ROBLEH ALI: And
what's interesting--

00:43:27.240 --> 00:43:29.945
because the English
Civil War was actually

00:43:29.945 --> 00:43:33.027
in the mid-17th century,
so shortly after that.

00:43:33.027 --> 00:43:34.610
So that's after the
powers of the king

00:43:34.610 --> 00:43:38.820
had been significantly
reduced, and became effectively

00:43:38.820 --> 00:43:41.010
a kind of
constitutional monarchy.

00:43:41.010 --> 00:43:44.300
So the Bank of England was sort
of set up around that time.

00:43:44.300 --> 00:43:46.850
GARY GENSLER: Same spirit
of checking the sovereign.

00:43:46.850 --> 00:43:48.650
So let's move on
a little bit, just

00:43:48.650 --> 00:43:50.910
so we can get to what
central banks are doing.

00:43:50.910 --> 00:43:53.300
But in essence, what
central banks do

00:43:53.300 --> 00:43:56.060
is they oversee
the banking system.

00:43:56.060 --> 00:44:01.210
I mean, back to they promote the
economy through stable prices,

00:44:01.210 --> 00:44:06.130
and in some countries, also
this concept of a dual mandate.

00:44:06.130 --> 00:44:08.590
They manage the Fiat
currency-- money--

00:44:08.590 --> 00:44:10.810
through supply and pricing.

00:44:10.810 --> 00:44:12.970
Oversee the banking system.

00:44:12.970 --> 00:44:16.570
And basically, are the
bankers to the government.

00:44:16.570 --> 00:44:18.790
When the government's
really in trouble,

00:44:18.790 --> 00:44:23.650
think back to the 1690s
when some noble lords

00:44:23.650 --> 00:44:26.760
were funding the king--

00:44:26.760 --> 00:44:29.400
it still happens that
central banks do sometimes

00:44:29.400 --> 00:44:31.010
fund governments.

00:44:31.010 --> 00:44:32.903
So the US Federal
Reserve balance sheet--

00:44:32.903 --> 00:44:34.320
I'm not going to
spend time on it.

00:44:34.320 --> 00:44:37.600
It will be in the
slides in Canvas.

00:44:37.600 --> 00:44:39.900
So let's talk about where
central banks approaches

00:44:39.900 --> 00:44:42.940
to blockchain and crypto.

00:44:42.940 --> 00:44:46.420
Some-- I would say a majority--
are monitoring and studying.

00:44:46.420 --> 00:44:49.300
The US Federal Reserve would be
this way, the European Central

00:44:49.300 --> 00:44:49.900
Bank.

00:44:49.900 --> 00:44:52.570
Rob has a better feel, because
he talks to central banks

00:44:52.570 --> 00:44:53.380
all the time.

00:44:53.380 --> 00:44:57.310
But monitor and study
is the dominant place.

00:44:57.310 --> 00:44:59.620
Restrict-- restrict its use.

00:44:59.620 --> 00:45:04.220
I'd say that the People's Bank
of China is more towards this.

00:45:04.220 --> 00:45:06.400
They're kind of a mixture
between monitor and study,

00:45:06.400 --> 00:45:10.300
because one of the readings was
actually from a senior policy

00:45:10.300 --> 00:45:13.150
person at the People's
Bank of China,

00:45:13.150 --> 00:45:15.490
and he's written some
remarkable pieces.

00:45:15.490 --> 00:45:19.720
Every few months, there's
a piece in like CNN,

00:45:19.720 --> 00:45:24.790
or CCN, which is a crypto
newsletter, or Coin Telegraph,

00:45:24.790 --> 00:45:27.700
that this one individual from
the Central Bank of China

00:45:27.700 --> 00:45:28.865
is writing these pieces.

00:45:28.865 --> 00:45:31.240
Now, I don't know a lot about
the Central Bank of China--

00:45:31.240 --> 00:45:34.450
he always puts at the bottom,
these are my personal views.

00:45:34.450 --> 00:45:36.100
But I have a
suspicion he would not

00:45:36.100 --> 00:45:38.530
be allowed to write these
things if it weren't something

00:45:38.530 --> 00:45:40.940
bubbling underneath.

00:45:40.940 --> 00:45:44.130
But you can restrict
the use of crypto.

00:45:44.130 --> 00:45:47.700
And some countries, like China,
and elsewhere are doing that.

00:45:47.700 --> 00:45:50.190
There's payment system
experimentation, which

00:45:50.190 --> 00:45:51.682
we're going to chat about.

00:45:51.682 --> 00:45:53.640
And then there's this
thing called central bank

00:45:53.640 --> 00:45:56.220
digital currency initiatives.

00:45:56.220 --> 00:45:59.422
And Rob and I know
the answer to this,

00:45:59.422 --> 00:46:00.630
but I'm curious to the group.

00:46:00.630 --> 00:46:02.730
Central bank digital
currency, having read all

00:46:02.730 --> 00:46:04.920
that you've read
for today, does it

00:46:04.920 --> 00:46:08.350
rely on blockchain technology?

00:46:08.350 --> 00:46:10.270
Show of hands, yes or no?

00:46:10.270 --> 00:46:12.970
So yes, it relies on--

00:46:12.970 --> 00:46:14.620
my hand won't matter.

00:46:14.620 --> 00:46:16.910
Does it rely on
blockchain technology?

00:46:16.910 --> 00:46:18.160
Central bank digital currency?

00:46:21.247 --> 00:46:22.330
I don't see a single hand.

00:46:22.330 --> 00:46:23.110
How about no?

00:46:23.110 --> 00:46:25.760
How many people think no?

00:46:25.760 --> 00:46:28.440
Oh, you did your readings well.

00:46:28.440 --> 00:46:30.000
Did you read it-- thank you.

00:46:30.000 --> 00:46:32.310
She's-- Simon, I'm-- you know.

00:46:32.310 --> 00:46:34.140
So central bank
digital currency is

00:46:34.140 --> 00:46:37.320
inspired by this whole
crypto finance movement,

00:46:37.320 --> 00:46:39.810
but it does not
necessarily depend

00:46:39.810 --> 00:46:41.680
upon blockchain technology.

00:46:41.680 --> 00:46:43.740
But I think it's
central to this course,

00:46:43.740 --> 00:46:46.590
and central to a study
of blockchain technology

00:46:46.590 --> 00:46:49.140
and money, because
it's absolutely

00:46:49.140 --> 00:46:51.900
inspired by this whole movement.

00:46:51.900 --> 00:46:53.820
Though, the first person
that wrote about it

00:46:53.820 --> 00:46:57.410
was Tobin in the
1980s, if I'm right.

00:46:57.410 --> 00:46:57.910
Right?

00:46:57.910 --> 00:47:00.210
ROBLEH ALI: [INAUDIBLE]

00:47:00.210 --> 00:47:03.240
GARY GENSLER: Yeah, 1987
or something, I think.

00:47:03.240 --> 00:47:06.960
Tobin wrote about
basically giving the public

00:47:06.960 --> 00:47:10.350
a direct tokenized means
beyond paper money--

00:47:10.350 --> 00:47:13.480
a digital means of an account.

00:47:13.480 --> 00:47:17.230
But most people would say,
central bank digital currency

00:47:17.230 --> 00:47:19.540
relies on blockchain
technology, and you've

00:47:19.540 --> 00:47:22.570
made me proud that you said no.

00:47:22.570 --> 00:47:25.090
Let's talk about
the pain points.

00:47:25.090 --> 00:47:26.740
This was last
Thursday's lecture,

00:47:26.740 --> 00:47:31.660
but there's some payment
system pain points.

00:47:31.660 --> 00:47:34.960
I added one or two
because of your feedback,

00:47:34.960 --> 00:47:39.190
but cost, delayed settlement,
chargebacks, fraud, privacy,

00:47:39.190 --> 00:47:43.290
financial inclusion,
and the like.

00:47:43.290 --> 00:47:49.420
And for Rob and Simon, this
was last Thursday's discussion.

00:47:49.420 --> 00:47:52.330
So some of what the
public sector is doing

00:47:52.330 --> 00:47:55.480
is non-blockchain
initiatives-- entirely

00:47:55.480 --> 00:47:57.370
non-blockchain initiatives.

00:47:57.370 --> 00:48:01.000
The European Union,
the US, others,

00:48:01.000 --> 00:48:03.580
are doing things
about faster payment.

00:48:03.580 --> 00:48:05.530
Basically trying to
move the payment system

00:48:05.530 --> 00:48:08.110
to 24 hours a day,
seven days a week,

00:48:08.110 --> 00:48:12.130
not locked up on the weekend,
where you can actually move.

00:48:12.130 --> 00:48:16.600
And that merchants can
do it as well as banks.

00:48:16.600 --> 00:48:18.790
So whether it's the
target instant payment

00:48:18.790 --> 00:48:21.610
system, or what's known
as TIPS in Europe,

00:48:21.610 --> 00:48:24.010
or faster payment task
force, which has led

00:48:24.010 --> 00:48:27.550
to a faster payment mechanism--

00:48:27.550 --> 00:48:29.680
I think, I'm guessing
Pria's husband's

00:48:29.680 --> 00:48:31.300
working on that, right?

00:48:31.300 --> 00:48:31.805
Does he--

00:48:31.805 --> 00:48:32.513
AUDIENCE: He was.

00:48:32.513 --> 00:48:35.140
GARY GENSLER: He was
working on the task force?

00:48:35.140 --> 00:48:38.110
Shrimp joined us last
Thursday, and he talked

00:48:38.110 --> 00:48:41.530
about-- he's at MasterCard.

00:48:41.530 --> 00:48:43.450
So a lot's going on.

00:48:43.450 --> 00:48:45.490
I just note--

00:48:45.490 --> 00:48:46.990
I put just two other countries.

00:48:46.990 --> 00:48:49.480
India's immediate
payment service

00:48:49.480 --> 00:48:54.582
is really government
sponsored, government pressed.

00:48:54.582 --> 00:48:56.790
I think one of the gentlemen
that works on it, Simon,

00:48:56.790 --> 00:49:00.540
you have speaking at MIT'S
campus in a few weeks.

00:49:00.540 --> 00:49:01.710
Arvent worked on it.

00:49:04.330 --> 00:49:06.810
And in the UK, where
they're saying--

00:49:06.810 --> 00:49:09.150
not only are we updating our
real time gross settlement

00:49:09.150 --> 00:49:12.030
system, but there's
a government mandate

00:49:12.030 --> 00:49:15.480
that banks have to open up
their bank accounts to what's

00:49:15.480 --> 00:49:18.210
called open API.

00:49:18.210 --> 00:49:21.210
A lot is going on,
non-blockchain related,

00:49:21.210 --> 00:49:25.690
related to payments, making
it faster and more access.

00:49:25.690 --> 00:49:28.750
But in the midst
of that, here is

00:49:28.750 --> 00:49:31.990
a little bit of what's happening
in the blockchain space.

00:49:31.990 --> 00:49:36.370
And with the help of the South
African white paper on this,

00:49:36.370 --> 00:49:37.960
I break it into three phases.

00:49:37.960 --> 00:49:41.050
So I thank South
Africa's central bank.

00:49:41.050 --> 00:49:42.940
First is phase one.

00:49:42.940 --> 00:49:44.870
Three countries wrote papers--

00:49:44.870 --> 00:49:48.100
Canada, Brazil, and Singapore.

00:49:48.100 --> 00:49:50.410
Canada and Singapore
even called them

00:49:50.410 --> 00:49:52.665
something-- it's called
Project Jasper in Canada,

00:49:52.665 --> 00:49:56.410
and Project Ubin in Singapore.

00:49:56.410 --> 00:49:58.780
And they did some
experimentation, all

00:49:58.780 --> 00:50:01.060
based on a Ethereum network--

00:50:01.060 --> 00:50:06.320
could you do a better payment
system based on Ethereum?

00:50:06.320 --> 00:50:11.360
So an open-source, blockchain,
permissionless system.

00:50:11.360 --> 00:50:13.980
And they tested out a new
real-time gross settlement

00:50:13.980 --> 00:50:14.480
system.

00:50:14.480 --> 00:50:16.700
And generally, the way
they do this is they

00:50:16.700 --> 00:50:19.750
get a group of banks
in their country--

00:50:19.750 --> 00:50:22.340
and if you were to read each
of their detailed reports,

00:50:22.340 --> 00:50:24.600
there's some similarities
and some differences--

00:50:24.600 --> 00:50:27.200
but by and large, get a group
of banks in your country,

00:50:27.200 --> 00:50:29.990
use the platform, try to do
a talking through, and see

00:50:29.990 --> 00:50:31.025
if it will work.

00:50:31.025 --> 00:50:31.790
Elene?

00:50:31.790 --> 00:50:33.830
AUDIENCE: So they built
a permissionless system?

00:50:33.830 --> 00:50:35.372
GARY GENSLER: They
were trying to see

00:50:35.372 --> 00:50:39.830
if they could use the Ethereum
network to build a better

00:50:39.830 --> 00:50:41.420
payment solution.

