00:51:16.890 --> 00:51:20.100
And all of these are
central bank focused.

00:51:20.100 --> 00:51:24.420
Japan and Europe added,
and South Africa.

00:51:24.420 --> 00:51:27.360
And all five initiatives--

00:51:27.360 --> 00:51:31.000
all have been
published already--

00:51:31.000 --> 00:51:35.280
were happening in those various
states in mid to late '17.

00:51:35.280 --> 00:51:38.340
And into '18, were
all on permission.

00:51:38.340 --> 00:51:41.220
They were looking at
Corda, Hyperledger Fabric,

00:51:41.220 --> 00:51:41.950
and Quorum--

00:51:41.950 --> 00:51:46.560
Quorum is the closed loop
system that JP Morgan.

00:51:46.560 --> 00:51:51.560
We talked about Hyperledger,
Fabric, and Corda.

00:51:51.560 --> 00:51:55.730
So I think, Elene, this kind of
starts to answer your question.

00:51:55.730 --> 00:51:58.100
That they then
said, well, no, it's

00:51:58.100 --> 00:52:00.110
not going to work
on a permissionless.

00:52:00.110 --> 00:52:01.640
Every one of them
in phase one said,

00:52:01.640 --> 00:52:03.140
we don't think this
is going to work

00:52:03.140 --> 00:52:04.320
on a permissionless system.

00:52:04.320 --> 00:52:08.840
Let's then go into a
phase two experimentation.

00:52:08.840 --> 00:52:13.340
We're now in kind of phase
three, or a third wave.

00:52:13.340 --> 00:52:15.650
We haven't heard from
Brazil recently--

00:52:15.650 --> 00:52:19.370
don't know whether that
project is basically stopped.

00:52:19.370 --> 00:52:22.730
But these are big countries
and big central banks,

00:52:22.730 --> 00:52:25.700
that are interested is-- can
there be a payment system

00:52:25.700 --> 00:52:27.840
solution?

00:52:27.840 --> 00:52:31.160
So I'm just going to talk
about Singapore for a minute,

00:52:31.160 --> 00:52:34.340
and give you a flavor for
outside of the readings,

00:52:34.340 --> 00:52:36.680
but a little bit of what
the Singapore project is.

00:52:36.680 --> 00:52:39.350
But it captures all
of these by just

00:52:39.350 --> 00:52:42.590
talking about this project.

00:52:42.590 --> 00:52:45.800
This is from their papers.

00:52:45.800 --> 00:52:49.280
But they really see that we're
in a multi-phase project.

00:52:49.280 --> 00:52:50.990
And they are willing
to publicly say,

00:52:50.990 --> 00:52:53.330
we're going to go further
than where we are right now.

00:52:53.330 --> 00:52:54.800
We want to get to
the place where

00:52:54.800 --> 00:52:57.950
we have domestic
delivery versus payment,

00:52:57.950 --> 00:53:00.800
and in the future payment
versus payment systems,

00:53:00.800 --> 00:53:02.510
money versus money.

00:53:02.510 --> 00:53:05.270
Delivery versus payment,
DVP, is basically

00:53:05.270 --> 00:53:08.540
a security versus money.

00:53:08.540 --> 00:53:13.540
So if you see the words DVP,
it's in the securities business

00:53:13.540 --> 00:53:18.550
where you move a security
and a payment simultaneously,

00:53:18.550 --> 00:53:20.500
and there's no credit risk.

00:53:20.500 --> 00:53:23.230
I will not give Rob the
security unless he gives me

00:53:23.230 --> 00:53:26.860
the cash, or vise versa.

00:53:26.860 --> 00:53:28.690
Ask me one day about when--

00:53:28.690 --> 00:53:33.910
before we had DVP, what
the markets were like.

00:53:33.910 --> 00:53:37.650
So Singapore is willing
to publicly announce--

00:53:37.650 --> 00:53:40.540
we're going to take this
as far as we can go,

00:53:40.540 --> 00:53:43.390
all the way to a
cross-border settlement

00:53:43.390 --> 00:53:46.690
of payments and securities
against each other,

00:53:46.690 --> 00:53:50.170
D versus P versus P,
is what they call it.

00:53:50.170 --> 00:53:52.940
The D you can think
of as securities.

00:53:52.940 --> 00:53:54.070
Will they succeed?

00:53:54.070 --> 00:53:56.330
Do they need to stay
on a blockchain?

00:53:56.330 --> 00:53:59.000
I can't predict that.

00:53:59.000 --> 00:54:02.780
But they're willing to say,
we're going to give this a try.

00:54:02.780 --> 00:54:04.530
Where are they right
now in phase two?

00:54:07.040 --> 00:54:10.070
Well, they tested Corda,
Hyperledger Fabric, and Quorum.

00:54:10.070 --> 00:54:12.050
And they have a
full 60-page report

00:54:12.050 --> 00:54:15.350
they published a month or two
ago about how did each of them

00:54:15.350 --> 00:54:20.360
work to do basically payment
versus payment, cash,

00:54:20.360 --> 00:54:22.310
large cash movements.

00:54:22.310 --> 00:54:24.680
But here are the six
criteria they tested,

00:54:24.680 --> 00:54:28.320
and they say they passed
every one of them.

00:54:28.320 --> 00:54:30.480
Now, I read the full
report, and I have to say,

00:54:30.480 --> 00:54:32.790
it struck me that they
probably did pass it.

00:54:32.790 --> 00:54:35.490
But I'm not enough of an
expert, and this stuff

00:54:35.490 --> 00:54:37.860
gets very granular,
and the question still

00:54:37.860 --> 00:54:42.510
is, could you just use an Oracle
database to do the same thing?

00:54:42.510 --> 00:54:44.550
And it's a fair question.

00:54:44.550 --> 00:54:47.550
But they tested it basically,
can you digitize the payments?

00:54:47.550 --> 00:54:50.130
Can you decentralize
the processing?

00:54:50.130 --> 00:54:51.720
Can you do the queuing--

00:54:51.720 --> 00:54:53.830
the queuing of payments.

00:54:53.830 --> 00:54:57.240
And a lot of
cross-entity payments,

00:54:57.240 --> 00:54:59.340
you have to net the payments.

00:54:59.340 --> 00:55:01.690
I'm going to pay Rob,
Rob is going to pay Hugo,

00:55:01.690 --> 00:55:03.460
Hugo is going to pay me--

00:55:03.460 --> 00:55:04.710
well, that doesn't make sense.

00:55:04.710 --> 00:55:08.550
You net it all, and it's
a queuing factor in all

00:55:08.550 --> 00:55:10.240
these real-time gross payments.

00:55:10.240 --> 00:55:10.915
Elene?

00:55:10.915 --> 00:55:12.790
AUDIENCE: So what is
