00:55:19.440 --> 00:55:21.060
it's clearly very centralized.

00:55:21.060 --> 00:55:22.820
What is the central [INAUDIBLE]?

00:55:22.820 --> 00:55:23.100
GARY GENSLER: It's up to them.

00:55:23.100 --> 00:55:24.642
And what they write
about, they think

00:55:24.642 --> 00:55:31.560
that you could lower the
single point of failure risk

00:55:31.560 --> 00:55:33.280
by not having the central bank.

00:55:33.280 --> 00:55:35.820
They actively-- this is a
central bank writing the paper

00:55:35.820 --> 00:55:40.170
saying, we could have more
resilience in the system

00:55:40.170 --> 00:55:43.460
if the database is
distributed amongst--

00:55:43.460 --> 00:55:46.050
in this case, they had
11 banks participating.

00:55:46.050 --> 00:55:48.570
And the 11 banks
have separate nodes.

00:55:48.570 --> 00:55:51.720
Now, it's still a
permissioned system.

00:55:51.720 --> 00:55:53.570
You might say, and
somehow the central bank

00:55:53.570 --> 00:55:57.120
has a notary node, maybe.

00:55:57.120 --> 00:55:59.160
But it's amongst the 11 banks.

00:55:59.160 --> 00:56:02.040
And that there would be more
resilience to this system

00:56:02.040 --> 00:56:03.300
than having it centralized.

00:56:03.300 --> 00:56:05.850
AUDIENCE: And the central bank
still does monetary policy?

00:56:05.850 --> 00:56:08.520
GARY GENSLER: Central bank
still does monetary policy.

00:56:08.520 --> 00:56:11.040
Rob, what do you
want to add to this?

00:56:11.040 --> 00:56:12.875
Because Rob swims
this lane, I don't.

00:56:12.875 --> 00:56:14.250
ROBLEH ALI: Yeah,
I mean, I think

00:56:14.250 --> 00:56:15.930
it's one of the big
challenges, right.

00:56:15.930 --> 00:56:21.480
Because the question of
how much the central bank

00:56:21.480 --> 00:56:24.310
consciously limits its own
power, I think is important.

00:56:24.310 --> 00:56:27.960
Because if you have
a system where--

00:56:27.960 --> 00:56:30.490
because I think there is
an instinct of certainly

00:56:30.490 --> 00:56:34.190
some central banks, they want to
maintain control of the system.

00:56:34.190 --> 00:56:36.080
Like, well, OK,
but we want to have

00:56:36.080 --> 00:56:38.490
a special node for
the central bank,

00:56:38.490 --> 00:56:40.520
we can do all this,
that, and the other.

00:56:40.520 --> 00:56:42.350
And my argument is,
you actually want

00:56:42.350 --> 00:56:44.990
to limit the power
of the central bank

00:56:44.990 --> 00:56:46.882
as far as you possibly
can, because it--

00:56:46.882 --> 00:56:48.340
to the extent that
the central bank

00:56:48.340 --> 00:56:50.007
has special powers
over the system,

00:56:50.007 --> 00:56:51.590
that creates a
weakness in the system.

00:56:51.590 --> 00:56:53.480
Because if that node
is then taken over,

00:56:53.480 --> 00:56:57.588
then whoever can go
change the system--

00:56:57.588 --> 00:56:59.630
has effectively all the
power of the central ban.

00:56:59.630 --> 00:57:06.020
Which takes away the
benefits of decentralization.

00:57:06.020 --> 00:57:08.360
To my mind, the point
of decentralization

00:57:08.360 --> 00:57:10.280
is increasing the
cost of the attack,

00:57:10.280 --> 00:57:13.700
by saying, well, to attack
the system, you have to attack

00:57:13.700 --> 00:57:15.540
50% of the nodes, or whatever.

00:57:15.540 --> 00:57:17.370
But if you have this one special
node that could do everything,

00:57:17.370 --> 00:57:18.953
then you only have
to attack one node.

00:57:18.953 --> 00:57:20.090
And it defeats the object.

00:57:20.090 --> 00:57:22.220
So I think when you're
speaking to central banks,

00:57:22.220 --> 00:57:24.470
you have to persuade
them of the need

00:57:24.470 --> 00:57:26.930
to have a system that they--

00:57:26.930 --> 00:57:29.030
like almost setting
up and let it go,

00:57:29.030 --> 00:57:31.550
rather than have to
continuously interfere with,

00:57:31.550 --> 00:57:33.510
an have to have these
special powers in it.

00:57:33.510 --> 00:57:38.050
GARY GENSLER: What's interesting
