01:03:31.570 --> 01:03:33.940
some readings, so I'm
not going to dive in now.

01:03:33.940 --> 01:03:36.810
So there's a little
bit of competition.

01:03:36.810 --> 01:03:38.660
So it's like Zahn's
earlier question--

01:03:38.660 --> 01:03:41.340
the private sector,
Circle, and Tether,

01:03:41.340 --> 01:03:43.560
and others are having
these stable value tokens.

01:03:43.560 --> 01:03:47.220
So there's a little bit of
competition coming that way.

01:03:47.220 --> 01:03:49.920
So the strategic question
for the central banks is,

01:03:49.920 --> 01:03:54.870
should we allow direct
access to digital reserves?

01:03:54.870 --> 01:03:56.970
We have this
intermediated central bank

01:03:56.970 --> 01:03:59.520
digital reserve
called bank deposits,

01:03:59.520 --> 01:04:01.980
but should we have
something direct to us?

01:04:01.980 --> 01:04:04.320
Like cash is a
direct relationship

01:04:04.320 --> 01:04:07.140
between the central
bank and the holder.

01:04:07.140 --> 01:04:10.380
That's really the strategic
question, when you--

01:04:10.380 --> 01:04:12.780
I believe when you move
away from the technology,

01:04:12.780 --> 01:04:15.420
you don't know have to
know about hash functions

01:04:15.420 --> 01:04:16.200
or anything.

01:04:16.200 --> 01:04:18.750
That's the strategic question.

01:04:18.750 --> 01:04:20.650
Why do I think there's
some opportunities?

01:04:20.650 --> 01:04:22.650
And we're going to dive
more into this Thursday,

01:04:22.650 --> 01:04:25.870
but I want Rob to see if he
wants to speak about this

01:04:25.870 --> 01:04:26.700
and tell us.

01:04:26.700 --> 01:04:29.040
I think this is
a real question--

01:04:29.040 --> 01:04:31.080
and Sweden has highlighted it--

01:04:31.080 --> 01:04:32.760
they want a
continued involvement

01:04:32.760 --> 01:04:33.840
in the means of payment.

01:04:33.840 --> 01:04:38.220
Sweden is already down to
about 2% of GDP, or 1/2% of GDP

01:04:38.220 --> 01:04:40.350
is their kronas--

01:04:40.350 --> 01:04:43.680
the physical kronas-- the
US is still at 8% or 9%.

01:04:43.680 --> 01:04:46.830
But they're saying
nobody is accepting

01:04:46.830 --> 01:04:49.500
physical kronas anymore
in Sweden and Norway,

01:04:49.500 --> 01:04:50.610
and so forth.

01:04:50.610 --> 01:04:53.670
Pretty soon, most retailers
will not take them.

01:04:53.670 --> 01:04:55.380
So they're saying,
maybe the government

01:04:55.380 --> 01:04:58.950
needs to have a continued
direct relationship.

01:04:58.950 --> 01:05:01.530
Could it promote competition
in the banking system?

01:05:01.530 --> 01:05:03.880
Because otherwise,
if you don't have it,

01:05:03.880 --> 01:05:06.030
then the banks are controlling
the payment system,

01:05:06.030 --> 01:05:07.500
and the means of payment.

01:05:07.500 --> 01:05:10.080
Promoting financial
inclusion-- not everybody

01:05:10.080 --> 01:05:11.190
will have a bank account.

01:05:11.190 --> 01:05:13.140
Well, maybe they could
have some digital form

01:05:13.140 --> 01:05:16.950
of central bank money
instead of a bank account.

01:05:16.950 --> 01:05:19.800
The pain points-- and I
would say for some countries,

01:05:19.800 --> 01:05:22.080
some countries are clearly
looking at central bank

01:05:22.080 --> 01:05:24.840
digital currencies to
avoid US sanctions.

01:05:24.840 --> 01:05:29.220
Venezuela and Iran both have
projects for central bank

01:05:29.220 --> 01:05:30.600
digital currency.

01:05:30.600 --> 01:05:31.560
Sorry, question?

01:05:34.140 --> 01:05:39.480
And so here, of course,
blockchain technology

01:05:39.480 --> 01:05:41.310
could be relevant.

01:05:41.310 --> 01:05:43.890
For these six reasons,
or five reasons,

01:05:43.890 --> 01:05:45.630
you didn't need
blockchain technology.

01:05:45.630 --> 01:05:48.255
But I'm going to say, blockchain
technology could be relevant--

01:05:48.255 --> 01:05:51.840
Fiat currencies on a ledger,
verification and networking

01:05:51.840 --> 01:05:55.470
costs are critical to
the economics of money.

01:05:55.470 --> 01:05:58.350
So I wouldn't count blockchain
technology out of this,

01:05:58.350 --> 01:06:01.020
because blockchain technology
can lower verification

01:06:01.020 --> 01:06:02.640
and networking costs.

01:06:02.640 --> 01:06:06.240
But I think we're too early
to know whether blockchain

01:06:06.240 --> 01:06:08.970
technology will be at the
center of central bank

01:06:08.970 --> 01:06:10.350
digital currency.

01:06:10.350 --> 01:06:12.880
But it could have an effect.

01:06:12.880 --> 01:06:15.075
So the challenges.

01:06:15.075 --> 01:06:16.950
And again, we'll dive
more of these Thursday.

01:06:19.142 --> 01:06:21.350
Rob, you want to say anything
about these challenges?

01:06:21.350 --> 01:06:22.790
ROBLEH ALI: Yeah,
I mean, I think

01:06:22.790 --> 01:06:24.380
Ben's speech was good on--

01:06:24.380 --> 01:06:25.410
GARY GENSLER: Ben
Broadbent's speech.

01:06:25.410 --> 01:06:26.660
ROBLEH ALI: Yeah, Ben
Broadbent's speech

01:06:26.660 --> 01:06:27.740
is good on that one.

01:06:27.740 --> 01:06:30.200
Because I think the
fundamental one is this--

01:06:30.200 --> 01:06:33.570
how do you fund a productive
enterprise in the real economy?

01:06:33.570 --> 01:06:34.570
Right, that's the real--

01:06:34.570 --> 01:06:35.240
GARY GENSLER: How do you--

01:06:35.240 --> 01:06:36.920
ROBLEH ALI: How do you
fund productive enterprise

01:06:36.920 --> 01:06:37.680
in the real economy?

01:06:37.680 --> 01:06:39.830
And at the moment, certainly
in the UK and Europe,

01:06:39.830 --> 01:06:41.930
and I guess to a lesser
extent in the US,

01:06:41.930 --> 01:06:44.550
but it's largely true
for the US, as well,

01:06:44.550 --> 01:06:48.960
is that you are very much
reliant on bank lending.

01:06:48.960 --> 01:06:52.820
And if you do something which
essentially drains deposits

01:06:52.820 --> 01:06:55.070
from banks, are you like
fundamentally changing

01:06:55.070 --> 01:06:56.630
the nature of the system?

01:06:56.630 --> 01:06:59.780
And how are you going
to create a system

01:06:59.780 --> 01:07:02.660
which allows people to fund
mortgages, or fund businesses,

01:07:02.660 --> 01:07:03.420
or whatever it is?

01:07:03.420 --> 01:07:06.230
And I think that's
the big challenge.

01:07:06.230 --> 01:07:09.260
So I think that's like the
central question, which

01:07:09.260 --> 01:07:11.580
I think is the
bullet three, effects

01:07:11.580 --> 01:07:13.490
on credit allocation
in the economy,

01:07:13.490 --> 01:07:16.940
is the thing that I think weighs
on central bankers the most.

01:07:16.940 --> 01:07:19.730
GARY GENSLER: So basically, if
you disintermediate the banks,

01:07:19.730 --> 01:07:21.560
and the banks are
not collecting--

01:07:21.560 --> 01:07:24.710
again, using US numbers--
$13 trillion of deposits,

01:07:24.710 --> 01:07:29.250
but only $12 trillion of
deposits, or maybe $6 trillion

01:07:29.250 --> 01:07:32.950
of deposits, what are we
doing to credit allocation?

01:07:32.950 --> 01:07:35.130
Because for three
to five centuries,

01:07:35.130 --> 01:07:38.880
or certainly since the
Industrial Revolution,

01:07:38.880 --> 01:07:42.390
banks form an important
feature in our economy

01:07:42.390 --> 01:07:45.970
to promote the
extension of credit.

01:07:45.970 --> 01:07:51.060
And we had this six or eight
lectures ago, this graph

01:07:51.060 --> 01:07:55.080
that in the US, debt to
our economy is about 3.8,

01:07:55.080 --> 01:08:01.380
or 380% of our economy in
debt it's not all bank debt,

01:08:01.380 --> 01:08:03.690
but bank debt is a
big piece of that.

01:08:03.690 --> 01:08:07.740
Can you move credit allocation
away from the banking system?

01:08:07.740 --> 01:08:11.280
Well, the answer has got
to be in some level, yes,

01:08:11.280 --> 01:08:15.750
but what are the pros
and cons of doing that?

01:08:15.750 --> 01:08:17.850
It's not whether you
can, it's whether it's

01:08:17.850 --> 01:08:20.729
a better system, a better
economy, better growth

01:08:20.729 --> 01:08:21.960
with or without it.

01:08:21.960 --> 01:08:22.800
Shawn?

01:08:22.800 --> 01:08:24.342
AUDIENCE: I was just
curious, can you

01:08:24.342 --> 01:08:26.880
use different interest
rates to represent

01:08:26.880 --> 01:08:28.490
different level of risk?

01:08:28.490 --> 01:08:32.776
And then use a differentiation
and interest point as a way

01:08:32.776 --> 01:08:35.109
to fund the corporates, so
they can get the loan faster,

01:08:35.109 --> 01:08:36.729
or they can get the [INAUDIBLE]?

01:08:36.729 --> 01:08:37.830
GARY GENSLER: So the
question is, could you use

01:08:37.830 --> 01:08:39.540
interest rates to try to do it?

01:08:39.540 --> 01:08:42.390
Which leads us to
design considerations.

01:08:45.220 --> 01:08:49.870
Which is basically, I
listed that the last one.

01:08:49.870 --> 01:08:52.660
You could have a central
bank digital currency

01:08:52.660 --> 01:08:54.670
that had zero interest rate--

01:08:54.670 --> 01:08:56.800
interestingly, we'll
talk more Thursday--

01:08:56.800 --> 01:08:57.760
Sweden said no.

01:08:57.760 --> 01:09:00.490
They think they'd put
an interest rate on it.

01:09:00.490 --> 01:09:02.370
But you could go
no interest rate.

01:09:02.370 --> 01:09:04.540
And I'd like to
hear your thoughts

01:09:04.540 --> 01:09:07.450
Thursday, well, why did
Sweden come out there?

01:09:07.450 --> 01:09:09.319
And what does that make sense?

01:09:09.319 --> 01:09:11.109
You could put limits
or caps on it,

01:09:11.109 --> 01:09:13.390
and say, these are only
low dollar accounts.

01:09:13.390 --> 01:09:18.310
You can only have X 100
euro, or X 100 krona,

01:09:18.310 --> 01:09:19.600
or Y number of dollars.

01:09:19.600 --> 01:09:22.000
And it's really just small
transactional accounts,

01:09:22.000 --> 01:09:27.130
equivalent to $20 bills,
not $100 or 500 euro notes.

01:09:27.130 --> 01:09:30.520
So you can put limits or
caps, or no interest rates,

01:09:30.520 --> 01:09:32.160
and so forth.

01:09:32.160 --> 01:09:35.420
Do you make it widely
accessible, and so forth?

01:09:35.420 --> 01:09:38.529
So there's all these
design considerations,

01:09:38.529 --> 01:09:41.112
which I'm guessing
Rob, you've talked

01:09:41.112 --> 01:09:42.279
to a bunch of central banks.

01:09:42.279 --> 01:09:46.120
Where do they come out on these
issues, as you see it, in 2018?

01:09:46.120 --> 01:09:48.540
ROBLEH ALI: You've got a lot
of different opinions on it.

01:09:48.540 --> 01:09:50.649
I think the limits and
caps thing is a hard thing

01:09:50.649 --> 01:09:51.910
to practically implement.

01:09:51.910 --> 01:09:56.145
That was always the
sort of skepticism

01:09:56.145 --> 01:09:58.270
around that-- it's like if
you have these accounts,

01:09:58.270 --> 01:10:00.830
and you say, well, we're going
to only have one per person,

01:10:00.830 --> 01:10:02.955
we're going to cap it at
a certain amount of money.

01:10:02.955 --> 01:10:05.530
What practically
happens in a wrong--

01:10:05.530 --> 01:10:07.550
is the government really
going to say, well, no,

01:10:07.550 --> 01:10:08.550
you can't put any more--

01:10:08.550 --> 01:10:11.480
Like there'll be a lot
of political pressure

01:10:11.480 --> 01:10:17.270
in any crisis, so I think caps
are really seen as viable.

01:10:17.270 --> 01:10:19.770
And then, I think the interest
bearing thing is interesting.

01:10:19.770 --> 01:10:21.270
I mean, the only
reason cash doesn't

01:10:21.270 --> 01:10:23.620
bear interest is because it's
technologically difficult

01:10:23.620 --> 01:10:25.930
to make a paper bear interest.

01:10:25.930 --> 01:10:30.000
So I think with
digital currency,

01:10:30.000 --> 01:10:31.960
they might as well give
yourself the option.

01:10:31.960 --> 01:10:33.835
Say, yeah, well, we can
set the interest rate

01:10:33.835 --> 01:10:37.358
to zero if you want to, but
why limit yourself to say,

01:10:37.358 --> 01:10:38.650
well, we won't charge interest?

01:10:38.650 --> 01:10:40.120
Because it's again--
it's like that's

01:10:40.120 --> 01:10:41.912
a limitation that comes
from the technology

01:10:41.912 --> 01:10:44.410
of physical banknotes,
and there's no real need

01:10:44.410 --> 01:10:48.410
to import it into the digital
world, when you could achieve

01:10:48.410 --> 01:10:50.410
the same effect by just
setting the rate at zero

01:10:50.410 --> 01:10:52.060
if you want to.

01:10:52.060 --> 01:10:55.030
GARY GENSLER: And one of the
reasons that some countries are

01:10:55.030 --> 01:10:57.070
exploring this
option, is they think

01:10:57.070 --> 01:10:59.080
it'll be easier to
do monetary policy,

01:10:59.080 --> 01:11:01.750
because you're going to have
negative interest rates.

01:11:01.750 --> 01:11:05.230
Physical cash makes it
hard for-- oh, nobody

01:11:05.230 --> 01:11:06.610
like that, huh?

01:11:06.610 --> 01:11:11.560
No, the two Elenes, you don't
like negative interest rates?

01:11:11.560 --> 01:11:17.620
But for a while, we effectively
had negative interest rates.

01:11:17.620 --> 01:11:20.740
Certainly for
corporate deposits.

01:11:20.740 --> 01:11:25.270
But if everything was digital,
and there was no physical cash,

01:11:25.270 --> 01:11:27.520
central banks say
we could actually

01:11:27.520 --> 01:11:33.164
go and have no lower bound, no
zero bound to interest rates.

01:11:33.164 --> 01:11:34.590
ROBLEH ALI: I guess
you, in a way,

01:11:34.590 --> 01:11:36.850
you don't necessarily need that.

01:11:36.850 --> 01:11:38.935
Because if you can
just create more money

01:11:38.935 --> 01:11:41.700
and pump it into the economy,
it has the same effect, right?

01:11:41.700 --> 01:11:43.450
GARY GENSLER: Right,
so what Rob is saying

01:11:43.450 --> 01:11:46.870
is you could affect
that by supply of money,

01:11:46.870 --> 01:11:48.730
rather than the
pricing of money.

01:11:48.730 --> 01:11:51.370
And so there's both.

01:11:51.370 --> 01:11:54.610
One of the most interesting to
me is the second bullet point--

01:11:54.610 --> 01:11:56.500
is a token or account based.

01:11:56.500 --> 01:11:59.950
And the two merge
together, in a sense.

01:11:59.950 --> 01:12:03.150
This piece of paper is a token.

01:12:03.150 --> 01:12:06.707
Nobody's keeping an account that
when I hand this to Rob-- here,

01:12:06.707 --> 01:12:09.160
you can take it, Rob.

01:12:09.160 --> 01:12:12.210
That's your fee, remember.

01:12:12.210 --> 01:12:15.580
So that's a token based
bit of money, that's

01:12:15.580 --> 01:12:17.770
what is called token based.

01:12:17.770 --> 01:12:19.960
Token based money
is more anonymous,

01:12:19.960 --> 01:12:21.760
and you can keep
it more anonymous.

01:12:21.760 --> 01:12:23.440
Account base is
when you're actually

01:12:23.440 --> 01:12:26.440
keeping the ownership
somewhere on a registry.

01:12:26.440 --> 01:12:29.320
Even though that $20 bill
is registered somewhere,

01:12:29.320 --> 01:12:33.010
it has a serial number, it's
a token based bit of money.

01:12:35.830 --> 01:12:41.100
The Swedes, interestingly, say
they'd have to change the law--

01:12:41.100 --> 01:12:44.520
their own central bank
laws-- for one of these two.

01:12:44.520 --> 01:12:45.690
And now I can't remember.

01:12:45.690 --> 01:12:49.470
But they have-- if
it's token base,

01:12:49.470 --> 01:12:51.210
it would come under
their e-money laws,

01:12:51.210 --> 01:12:54.480
and I think they don't need
to change the law to do that.

01:12:54.480 --> 01:12:58.890
But in Sweden, they would have
to change their central bank

01:12:58.890 --> 01:13:01.800
laws to do e-deposits,
because they would literally

01:13:01.800 --> 01:13:05.100
be opening up their central
bank to something other

01:13:05.100 --> 01:13:06.450
than commercial banks.

01:13:06.450 --> 01:13:10.260
That's it-- they have to go
to their legislative body

01:13:10.260 --> 01:13:13.710
and parliament to actually
do an account based, and not

01:13:13.710 --> 01:13:16.770
a token based, if I recall.

01:13:16.770 --> 01:13:18.410
So there's some
also legal reasons

01:13:18.410 --> 01:13:20.160
why you might need to
do one or the other,

01:13:20.160 --> 01:13:22.957
but one would have more
anonymity than the other.

01:13:22.957 --> 01:13:24.540
ROBLEH ALI: I think
it's worth noting,

01:13:24.540 --> 01:13:27.210
on these token versus
account models,

01:13:27.210 --> 01:13:29.798
it's not well-defined what
people mean when they say taken

01:13:29.798 --> 01:13:30.340
and accounts.

01:13:30.340 --> 01:13:32.700
So different central
banks will say this,

01:13:32.700 --> 01:13:34.680
and mean different things.

01:13:34.680 --> 01:13:37.480
And also people who work on
Bitcoin will think about--

01:13:37.480 --> 01:13:40.940
so when I see tokens, I think
about particular structure

01:13:40.940 --> 01:13:42.960
and transactions,
which Bitcoin has.

01:13:42.960 --> 01:13:44.650
And when I think
about accounts, I

01:13:44.650 --> 01:13:47.320
think of structure of
transactions that Ethereum has.

01:13:47.320 --> 01:13:49.728
And that's how I distinguish
between those two things.

01:13:49.728 --> 01:13:52.020
But I think having spoken to
different central bankers,

01:13:52.020 --> 01:13:56.432
they think about it differently,
because e-money is like--

01:13:56.432 --> 01:13:57.640
you could think about it as--

01:13:57.640 --> 01:14:00.820
I mean to me, that's an
account based system.

01:14:00.820 --> 01:14:02.922
But some bankers
think about it--

01:14:02.922 --> 01:14:05.130
some central bankers think
about that as token based.

01:14:05.130 --> 01:14:08.400
So it's worth noting
that the definitions are

01:14:08.400 --> 01:14:11.190
very fluid in this area.

01:14:11.190 --> 01:14:15.493
GARY GENSLER: So we're going
to save this for Thursday.

01:14:15.493 --> 01:14:16.910
I'm not going to
go through this--

01:14:16.910 --> 01:14:18.620
it was in one of the readings.

01:14:18.620 --> 01:14:21.650
Garratt, who
testified in Congress,

01:14:21.650 --> 01:14:23.820
was so popular with
this, then the Bank

01:14:23.820 --> 01:14:25.820
of International Settlement
picked up this thing

01:14:25.820 --> 01:14:27.770
called the money flower.

01:14:27.770 --> 01:14:30.270
But I'm going to save this, I
want to kick this to Thursday.

01:14:30.270 --> 01:14:32.270
But it's basically
the four things--

01:14:32.270 --> 01:14:35.480
widely accessible, is it
digital, is its central bank,

01:14:35.480 --> 01:14:37.090
is it token based?

01:14:37.090 --> 01:14:40.550
And depending upon
where these intersect,

01:14:40.550 --> 01:14:42.140
you can take any form of money.

01:14:42.140 --> 01:14:44.790
You could say, well, it's
not central bank issued,

01:14:44.790 --> 01:14:48.780
its token based,
private digital tokens,

01:14:48.780 --> 01:14:52.500
is down on the right hand corner
is one little piece of it.

01:14:52.500 --> 01:14:57.060
It's just a way to take these
four important features.

01:14:57.060 --> 01:15:01.640
And we already have
central bank digital money,

01:15:01.640 --> 01:15:04.840
which is in the middle of all
this, it's called reserves.

01:15:04.840 --> 01:15:08.870
But we're going to hold
this for Thursday--

01:15:08.870 --> 01:15:11.540
but this crazy
little money flower,

01:15:11.540 --> 01:15:14.320
central bankers who
are in this world,

01:15:14.320 --> 01:15:18.260
they've been using this, because
this Professor Garratt came up

01:15:18.260 --> 01:15:19.400
with it.

01:15:19.400 --> 01:15:21.037
I mean, I've seen
this in other papers.

01:15:21.037 --> 01:15:22.370
ROBLEH ALI: It's very important.

01:15:22.370 --> 01:15:23.640
GARY GENSLER: They
love it, you know.

01:15:23.640 --> 01:15:24.350
I don't know.

01:15:24.350 --> 01:15:27.800
Money and flowers
together, there you go.

