01:16:03.800 --> 01:16:07.240
that project is that it was
actually live and out there

01:16:07.240 --> 01:16:11.073
in the hands of people,
paying for things in shops.

01:16:11.073 --> 01:16:12.740
And I think that's
what distinguishes it

01:16:12.740 --> 01:16:16.800
from a lot of the
other projects.

01:16:16.800 --> 01:16:18.965
So for example, the
ones that Gary's talked

01:16:18.965 --> 01:16:21.810
about earlier in, say,
Singapore and Canada,

01:16:21.810 --> 01:16:24.590
are really just in-house
creative concepts,

01:16:24.590 --> 01:16:26.810
whereas the Uruguay
project was something

01:16:26.810 --> 01:16:31.860
that actually has worked, and
they've taken an early form.

01:16:31.860 --> 01:16:35.900
The Swedish one, again,
is fairly early stage.

01:16:35.900 --> 01:16:37.560
The e-krona is
not out there yet,

01:16:37.560 --> 01:16:39.750
they're just starting
to explore it.

01:16:39.750 --> 01:16:41.300
The Tunisia one
was interesting--

01:16:41.300 --> 01:16:43.793
I've spoken to one of
the guys working on that.

01:16:43.793 --> 01:16:46.210
And again, that's interesting
because it's a live project.

01:16:46.210 --> 01:16:48.980
It's continuing-- unlike
the Uruguayan project,

01:16:48.980 --> 01:16:51.080
it's a continuing project.

01:16:51.080 --> 01:16:53.330
So it'll be interesting to
see how it plays out there.

01:16:53.330 --> 01:16:56.303
And I think the reason being
is a lot of the thing that

01:16:56.303 --> 01:16:58.220
puts off central banks
from actually doing it,

01:16:58.220 --> 01:17:00.678
is they don't know what effect
it would have on the banking

01:17:00.678 --> 01:17:01.750
system, or whatever.

01:17:01.750 --> 01:17:03.807
And I think you
will start to see--

01:17:03.807 --> 01:17:05.640
when you start to see
people actually trying

01:17:05.640 --> 01:17:07.730
it, and deploying a central
bank digital currency

01:17:07.730 --> 01:17:10.040
in the real economy,
then you will

01:17:10.040 --> 01:17:13.922
have a real pilot, or
a real world example,

01:17:13.922 --> 01:17:15.380
that you can then
research and say,

01:17:15.380 --> 01:17:16.838
well, actually the
effect was this.

01:17:16.838 --> 01:17:19.690
Because at the moment, a lot of
the debate around central bank

01:17:19.690 --> 01:17:21.440
digital currency, what
would be the effect

01:17:21.440 --> 01:17:22.910
be on the banking system?

01:17:22.910 --> 01:17:24.940
This is conjecture,
you can build a model.

01:17:24.940 --> 01:17:25.940
But it's very difficult.

01:17:25.940 --> 01:17:28.107
But I think once you start
to see countries actually

01:17:28.107 --> 01:17:30.040
issue them, then you
get the evidence in.

01:17:30.040 --> 01:17:33.190
And then I think you'll
see a cascade effect.

01:17:33.190 --> 01:17:35.690
It will be very quickly, then,
the technology is proven out,

01:17:35.690 --> 01:17:37.732
and then more and more
countries will issue them.

01:17:37.732 --> 01:17:39.470
And also because of
the funding effect,

01:17:39.470 --> 01:17:44.100
Gary talked earlier
about the cash--

01:17:44.100 --> 01:17:48.530
like US dollars, physical cash,
is effectively $1.6 trillion

01:17:48.530 --> 01:17:51.230
of interest-free borrowing
by the US government.

01:17:51.230 --> 01:17:54.540
And if, say, the US government
issued digital dollars,

01:17:54.540 --> 01:17:58.787
then arguably you could
retire half the national debt

01:17:58.787 --> 01:17:59.870
and replace it with money.

01:17:59.870 --> 01:18:02.600
So there are these big
fiscal implications.

01:18:02.600 --> 01:18:04.310
And the Body of the
Commonwealth paper,

01:18:04.310 --> 01:18:06.860
which my colleagues at
[INAUDIBLE] wrote, I think,

01:18:06.860 --> 01:18:10.160
two years ago, sort of
addresses that fiscal element.

01:18:10.160 --> 01:18:12.950
And I think that will be a
big attraction to politicians

01:18:12.950 --> 01:18:14.310
looking to spend money.

